org.opendatakit.aggregate.odktables.rest

Class ConflictType

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.opendatakit.aggregate.odktables.rest.ConflictType

  • public class ConflictType
extends Object
    This class stores ints that should be stored in the client-side (device) data table's TableConstants.CONFLICT_TYPE column. This column represents the reason that the rows are labeled as conflict.

    There are essentially three scenarios to consider. All of which will have the rows' TableConstants.SYNC_STATE set to SyncState.conflicting:

    1. Two users have modified the same row, one has synched, the other pull those changes
      • In this case neither row has been deleted. The local row will have TableConstants.CONFLICT_TYPE equal to LOCAL_UPDATED_UPDATED_VALUES, and the server row will have TableConstants.CONFLICT_TYPE equal to SERVER_UPDATED_UPDATED_VALUES.
    2. The row has been deleted on the server, and the local user has edited their local version
      • In this case the server row is considered deleted. Its TableConstants.CONFLICT_TYPE row will be set to SERVER_DELETED_OLD_VALUES. The values in that row will be the contents of that row on the server at the time of deletion. The local row, which had been edited and been in SyncState.updating before the sync (and thus why it was not deleted outright), will have TableConstants.CONFLICT_TYPE set to LOCAL_UPDATED_UPDATED_VALUES. TODO: what happens if both versions are deleted, but the row versions were different? Is this case handled appropriately? Unclear...
    3. The local row has been deleted, but a newer version has been updated on the server
      • In this case the local row will have TableConstants.CONFLICT_TYPE equal to LOCAL_DELETED_OLD_VALUES. It will have the values that were in the row at the time of deletion. These may differ from the last synced version of the row--i.e. updates may have been performed before deletion, meaning the sync state moved from SyncState.rest to SyncState.updating to SyncState.deleting. The server row meanwhile will have TableConstants.CONFLICT_TYPE set to SERVER_UPDATED_UPDATED_VALUES. The contents of this row will be the latest version of the updated row on the server.
